<p>The Yorkshire Terrier puppy is feeding at the opposite extreme to almost every other breed we cover. It isn't a fast-growing giant whose joints you're protecting from overfeeding, nor a long-backed Dachshund whose spine you're guarding — the Yorkie's whole challenge is being <strong>genuinely, remarkably tiny</strong>. A young Yorkie pup can weigh less than a bag of sugar, grows to just 2–3.5kg, and that size flips the priorities entirely. The big risk isn't too many calories — it's too few, too far apart. A toy puppy has almost no fat reserves and a fast metabolism, so a missed or delayed meal can drop its blood sugar dangerously low (hypoglycaemia), causing wobbliness, weakness and even seizures. Add a jaw so small that many normal kibbles are physically too big to eat, and some of the worst dental disease of any breed, and the brief becomes clear: <strong>steady energy, fed little and often, in a tiny low-sugar piece — from the very first bowl.</strong></p>

<p>This guide is written from experience. Our own dog <strong>Milo is a 12-year-old Labrador/Lurcher rescue</strong> who's wheat-sensitive — we've lived the daily reality of feeding for the long game, weighing meals and matching food to the dog in front of us. A Yorkie needs that same care, only the thing you're protecting is its blood sugar and its little teeth, not its gut or its joints. Below are the UK puppy foods we'd point a Yorkie owner towards for 2026, ranked and explained, plus an honest look at whether a true toy-breed specialist is worth it for a pup that can't manage a normal kibble.</p>

