<p>Across all of it, three rules matter most for a Yorkie: <strong>never let blood sugar crash</strong> — feed little and often, keep glucose to hand, and know the hypoglycaemia warning signs; <strong>match the food to the mouth</strong> — a small enough piece (or a soft format) so a tiny jaw can actually eat it; and <strong>defend the teeth from day one</strong> — a low-sugar diet plus daily brushing, because dental disease is the breed's most predictable problem. Any episode of weakness, wobbliness, collapse or persistent refusal to eat in a toy puppy is a same-day vet matter, not something to wait out.</p>

